  "executive_summary": "For a small-team courier company needing reliable, extensible delivery notifications, Option B (event-driven with a lightweight queue) is the recommended approach. It naturally decouples the delivery domain from notification dispatch, makes adding channels trivial, and provides built-in retry semantics — all without requiring complex infrastructure. The 5-minute latency tolerance is the key constraint that unlocks this: it eliminates the only real argument for synchronous calls (immediacy) while aligning perfectly with queue-based processing. However, the recommendation is calibrated for a 3-engineer team — a managed queue service (SQS, Cloud Tasks, or even a Postgres-backed job table) rather than self-hosted Kafka/RabbitMQ.",

  "architecture": {
    "components": [
      {
        "name": "Delivery Service",
        "responsibility": "Manages delivery lifecycle (picked up, in transit, delivered, failed). Publishes domain events on state transitions. Owns NO notification logic.",
        "boundaries": "Knows nothing about email, SMS, or any notification channel. Its only coupling to notifications is the event schema it publishes."
      },
      {
        "name": "Event Bus / Job Queue",
        "responsibility": "Durably stores domain events and guarantees at-least-once delivery to consumers. Provides retry with backoff, dead-letter semantics, and visibility timeout.",
        "boundaries": "Transport only — no business logic. Accepts structured events, delivers them to subscribed workers."
      },
      {
        "name": "Notification Dispatcher",
        "responsibility": "Consumes delivery events, resolves customer notification preferences (channels, opt-outs), and fans out to channel-specific senders.",
        "boundaries": "Owns the mapping from 'what happened' to 'who gets notified and how'. Does NOT own delivery domain logic or channel-specific send mechanics."
      },
      {
        "name": "Channel Adapters (Email, SMS, future Push/WhatsApp)",
        "responsibility": "Each adapter implements a uniform SendNotification interface and translates to provider-specific API calls (SendGrid, Twilio, etc.).",
        "boundaries": "One adapter per channel. Each is independently deployable, testable, and replaceable. Provider switch (e.g., Twilio → Vonage) is isolated to one adapter."
      },
      {
        "name": "Dead Letter Queue + Alert",
        "responsibility": "Captures notifications that exhaust all retry attempts. Triggers an alert so the team can investigate and manually replay.",
        "boundaries": "Failure boundary — nothing in the DLQ is silently dropped."
      }
    ],
    "interfaces": [
      {
        "from": "Delivery Service",
        "to": "Event Bus",
        "contract": "Publishes DeliveryStatusChanged events: { deliveryId, customerId, status, timestamp, metadata }",
        "coupling_type": "loose — fire-and-forget publish; delivery service doesn't know or care who consumes"
      },
      {
        "from": "Event Bus",
        "to": "Notification Dispatcher",
        "contract": "At-least-once delivery of DeliveryStatusChanged events with visibility timeout and retry policy",
        "coupling_type": "loose — dispatcher subscribes to event type, not to delivery service directly"
      },
      {
        "from": "Notification Dispatcher",
        "to": "Channel Adapters",
        "contract": "SendNotification(channel, recipient, templateId, templateData) → Success | TransientFailure | PermanentFailure",
        "coupling_type": "low — dispatcher calls a uniform interface; adapter selection is via strategy pattern or registry"
      },
      {
        "from": "Channel Adapters",
        "to": "External Providers (SendGrid, Twilio, etc.)",
        "contract": "Provider-specific REST/SDK calls, isolated behind the adapter boundary",
        "coupling_type": "tight but contained — tightly coupled to provider API, but the blast radius is one adapter file"
      }
    ],
    "data_flow": "1. Delivery Service transitions a delivery to a new status (e.g., 'out_for_delivery'). 2. It publishes a DeliveryStatusChanged event to the queue. 3. Notification Dispatcher picks up the event, looks up customer preferences, and determines which channels to notify. 4. For each channel, it invokes the corresponding Channel Adapter. 5. The adapter calls the external provider. 6. On transient failure, the message returns to the queue with exponential backoff. 7. After max retries, the message lands in the Dead Letter Queue and an alert fires.",
    "patterns_used": [
      {
        "pattern": "Domain Events",
        "rationale": "Delivery status changes are meaningful domain events. Publishing them decouples the delivery bounded context from all downstream concerns (notifications, analytics, partner updates). This is the natural seam in the system."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "At-Least-Once Delivery with Idempotency",
        "rationale": "The reliability requirement ('never silently drop') maps directly to at-least-once queue semantics. Channel adapters must be idempotent (use provider-level deduplication keys) to handle redelivery safely."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Strategy Pattern (Channel Adapters)",
        "rationale": "The explicit requirement to add new channels (push, WhatsApp) in the future. A channel registry with a uniform interface means adding a channel is: implement the interface, register it, deploy. Zero changes to dispatcher logic."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Dead Letter Queue",
        "rationale": "Directly satisfies 'failed notification must be retried, not silently dropped'. After exhausting retries, messages are preserved for manual inspection rather than lost."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Transactional Outbox (recommended for production)",
        "rationale": "Prevents the dual-write problem: delivery status saved to DB but event publish fails (or vice versa). For a small team, a simple Postgres-backed outbox table polled on an interval is sufficient — no need for CDC tooling."
      }
    ]
  },

  "domain_model": {
    "bounded_contexts": [
      {
        "name": "Delivery",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": ["Delivery (root: deliveryId, tracks status lifecycle, emits DeliveryStatusChanged events)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Notification",
        "classification": "supporting",
        "aggregates": ["NotificationRequest (root: notificationId, tracks send attempts and status per channel)", "CustomerPreferences (root: customerId, stores channel opt-ins and contact details)"]
      }
    ],
    "context_map": [
      {
        "upstream": "Delivery",
        "downstream": "Notification",
        "relationship": "Customer-Supplier via Domain Events. Delivery defines the event schema. Notification consumes it through an Anti-Corruption Layer that translates delivery events into notification commands. Delivery team has no obligation to accommodate notification-specific fields."
      }
    ]
  },

  "trade_offs": [
    {
      "decision": "Option B (event-driven) over Option A (synchronous REST)",
      "gains": "Decoupled delivery and notification logic; built-in retry/backoff from queue; adding channels requires zero changes to delivery service; delivery service latency unaffected by slow providers; partial failures don't block delivery status updates",
      "sacrifices": "Introduces a queue dependency (operational surface area); slightly more complex local development setup; event ordering is not guaranteed (acceptable here); eventual consistency between delivery status and notification send",
      "alternatives_considered": [
        "Option A: Synchronous REST — simpler initially but creates tight coupling, retry logic must be hand-rolled in the delivery service, adding channels requires modifying the delivery service, and a slow/down provider blocks delivery processing. Rejected because reliability and extensibility requirements directly conflict with synchronous coupling.",
        "Hybrid: Synchronous for email (most common), async for rest — adds complexity without clear benefit; the 5-minute latency tolerance means async is fine for all channels."
      ]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Managed queue service (SQS/Cloud Tasks) over self-hosted broker (RabbitMQ/Kafka)",
      "gains": "Near-zero operational burden for a 3-engineer team; built-in retry, DLQ, and monitoring; no broker patching, scaling, or cluster management",
      "sacrifices": "Vendor lock-in to cloud provider; less control over routing topology; per-message costs (negligible at courier-company scale)",
      "alternatives_considered": [
        "Postgres-backed job queue (e.g., graphile-worker, pgboss) — viable middle ground if the team wants to avoid cloud queue services entirely; uses existing Postgres infrastructure; trades queue features for operational simplicity"
      ]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Transactional Outbox over direct event publish",
      "gains": "Eliminates dual-write problem — guarantees event is published if and only if the delivery status is persisted; crash-safe",
      "sacrifices": "Adds a polling mechanism or trigger; slightly increases write latency (still well within 5-minute tolerance); requires an outbox table and a relay process",
      "alternatives_considered": [
        "Direct publish after DB commit — simpler but risks lost events on crash between commit and publish; acceptable only if the team is willing to tolerate rare event loss (conflicts with reliability requirement)"
      ]
    }
  ],

  "flexibility_points": [
    {
      "area": "Channel Adapters",
      "evolution_path": "Adding WhatsApp or push notifications requires: (1) implement the ChannelAdapter interface, (2) register in the channel registry, (3) deploy. No changes to Delivery Service or Notification Dispatcher. This is the primary extensibility axis the requirements demand."
    },
    {
      "area": "Provider Swaps",
      "evolution_path": "Switching from Twilio to Vonage for SMS is isolated to the SMS adapter. No other component is affected. Can be done with a feature flag for gradual migration."
    },
    {
      "area": "Notification Templates",
      "evolution_path": "Template content and formatting can evolve independently of dispatch logic. Store templates externally (DB or files) so product/ops can update wording without code deploys."
    },
    {
      "area": "Event Consumers",
      "evolution_path": "New consumers (analytics, partner webhooks, audit log) can subscribe to the same DeliveryStatusChanged events without modifying the Delivery Service. The event bus is the natural extension point."
    }
  ],

  "rigidity_points": [
    {
      "area": "Event Schema (DeliveryStatusChanged)",
      "reason": "This is the contract between Delivery and Notification contexts. Changes to the schema require coordination. Use schema versioning from day one — include a version field and design consumers to tolerate unknown fields. This rigidity is intentional: the event schema should be stable because it represents a well-understood domain concept."
    },
    {
      "area": "At-Least-Once Semantics",
      "reason": "The system commits to at-least-once delivery, which means ALL channel adapters MUST be idempotent. This is a hard architectural constraint. Every new adapter must handle duplicate delivery gracefully (via provider-side dedup keys or local dedup tracking). This rigidity is load-bearing — relaxing it breaks the reliability guarantee."
    },
    {
      "area": "Queue Infrastructure Choice",
      "reason": "Migrating from one queue system to another (e.g., SQS to RabbitMQ) is painful. Mitigate by wrapping queue access behind a thin interface, but realistically the queue choice is sticky."
    }
  ],

