    "recommended_approach": "Implement Option B (event-driven) with a Postgres-backed job queue as the pragmatic sweet spot for a 3-engineer team. Specifically: (1) Add an outbox table to the delivery database. When a delivery status changes, insert the event into the outbox within the same transaction. (2) Run a lightweight poller (cron or background worker) that reads unpublished outbox rows, dispatches them to the Notification Dispatcher, and marks them as published. (3) The Notification Dispatcher resolves customer preferences and fans out to Channel Adapters. (4) Each adapter implements a uniform interface and calls the external provider with an idempotency key. (5) Failed sends are retried with exponential backoff (managed by the job queue). After max retries, the job moves to a failed-jobs table (acting as DLQ) and an alert fires. Start with pgboss (Node.js) or a simple custom outbox-poller if using another stack. Migrate to SQS/Cloud Tasks only if throughput demands it — for a courier company's notification volume, Postgres will handle it comfortably.",
    "files_to_create_or_modify": [
      "src/delivery/events/DeliveryStatusChanged.ts — Domain event definition with schema version",
      "src/delivery/outbox/outbox.table.sql — Outbox table migration (id, event_type, payload, created_at, published_at)",
      "src/delivery/outbox/OutboxRelay.ts — Polls outbox, publishes to notification dispatcher, marks published",
      "src/notification/dispatcher/NotificationDispatcher.ts — Consumes events, resolves preferences, fans out to adapters",
      "src/notification/channels/ChannelAdapter.ts — Interface: send(recipient, template, data) → Result",
      "src/notification/channels/EmailAdapter.ts — SendGrid/SES implementation",
      "src/notification/channels/SmsAdapter.ts — Twilio implementation",
      "src/notification/channels/ChannelRegistry.ts — Maps channel type → adapter instance",
      "src/notification/preferences/CustomerPreferences.ts — Repository for channel opt-ins and contact details",
      "src/notification/dlq/FailedNotificationHandler.ts — Logs, alerts, and stores failed notifications for manual review"
    ],
    "patterns_to_follow": "Uniform ChannelAdapter interface for all channels. Idempotency keys on every provider call. Outbox pattern for event reliability. Exponential backoff with jitter on retries. Schema versioning on domain events from day one.",
    "pitfalls_to_avoid": [
      "DO NOT put notification logic in the Delivery Service — this is the #1 mistake that makes the system rigid and hard to extend",
      "DO NOT use fire-and-forget HTTP calls to providers without retry — this directly violates the reliability requirement",
      "DO NOT self-host Kafka or RabbitMQ with a 3-person team — the operational burden will consume your capacity",
      "DO NOT embed customer contact details in the event payload — always fetch at dispatch time to respect opt-outs and updates",
      "DO NOT skip idempotency — at-least-once delivery WILL produce duplicates; handle them or your customers get spammed",
      "DO NOT build a custom retry framework — use your job queue's built-in retry mechanics"
    ]
  },

  "escalations": [],

  "confidence": {
    "level": 90,
    "high_confidence_areas": [
      "Option B is clearly superior given the stated constraints (reliability > latency, extensibility, small team)",
      "Postgres-backed job queue is the right infrastructure choice for this team size and volume",
      "Channel Adapter pattern with uniform interface is the correct extensibility mechanism",
      "Outbox pattern is necessary to prevent silent event loss"
    ],
    "low_confidence_areas": [
      "Specific provider choices (SendGrid vs SES, Twilio vs alternatives) — depends on existing vendor relationships and pricing",
      "Exact retry policy parameters (max retries, backoff intervals) — should be tuned based on provider SLAs and observed failure rates"
    ],
    "assumptions": [
      "Notification volume is proportional to a courier company's delivery volume — thousands to low tens-of-thousands per day, not millions",
      "The team already operates a relational database (Postgres assumed) for the delivery service",
      "The team has basic cloud infrastructure but not a dedicated platform/SRE function",
      "Customer notification preferences (channel opt-ins, contact details) are managed somewhere in the system"
    ]
  }
}

